**Status:** ⏳ Coming soon  
**Estimated AWS cost:** $0 (free tier)  
**Time to build:** ~2 hours  

---

## Business Problem

A misconfigured AWS account is one of the most common causes of data breaches and unexpected costs. S3 buckets left public, root accounts without MFA, and unused access keys are found in real customer environments every day. This project documents a systematic security review and hardening of an AWS account — the same process a TAM or SA would walk a customer through.

---

## Services Used

| Service | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| IAM | User, role, and policy configuration — least privilege |
| CloudTrail | Audit logging — every API call recorded |
| AWS Config | Continuous compliance monitoring against security rules |
| Security Hub | Aggregated security findings across services |
| IAM Credential Report | Snapshot of all users, key ages, and MFA status |

---

## Security Checks Performed

### IAM
- [ ] Root account MFA enabled
- [ ] No root access keys exist
- [ ] Password policy enforced (length, complexity, rotation)
- [ ] All IAM users have MFA enabled
- [ ] No users with unused access keys older than 90 days
- [ ] IAM credential report generated and reviewed

### CloudTrail
- [ ] Trail enabled in us-east-1
- [ ] Logs delivered to S3 bucket
- [ ] Log file validation enabled

### AWS Config
- [ ] Config enabled and recording
- [ ] Core managed rules enabled (list below)
- [ ] Non-compliant findings documented
- [ ] Remediation applied and re-evaluated

### Config Rules Enabled
| Rule | What it checks |
|------|---------------|
| `root-account-mfa-enabled` | Root account has MFA |
| `iam-password-policy` | Password policy meets requirements |
| `s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited` | No S3 buckets are publicly readable |
| `cloudtrail-enabled` | CloudTrail is active |
| `access-keys-rotated` | Access keys rotated within 90 days |

